            "title": "Human Language Technology for Language Learning (HLT4LL)",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2012
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": null
                }
            },
            "description": "The HLT4LL 2013 symposium addresses the possibilities and challenges of using human language technologies (HLT) for language learning (LL) (HLT4LL). We define HLT4LL as any use or integration of language and speech technology to structure, facilitate (support) and evaluate the language learning process. To fully acknowledge and address the complexity of this interdisciplinary domain, the symposium brings together representatives from various but related research fields: language and speech technology, computational linguistics, corpus linguistics (learner and bilingual corpora), data-driven language learning, (second) language acquisition, language pedagogy, computer assisted language learning (CALL), educational technology, semantic web, artificial intelligence, human-computer interaction (HCI/CHI), etc.\nThis symposium is intended to provide a state-of-the-art overview of this interdisciplinary domain for people from academia, educational institutions, industry, as well as for policymakers.\n\nThe symposium takes place in Stellenbosch, South-Africa, on 11-12 November 2013.\n\nKeynote speakers: Nick C. Ellis (University of Michigan), Maxine Eskenazi (Carnegie Mellon University), John Nerbonne (University of Groningen), Mathias Schulze (University of Waterloo), Isabel Trancoso (INESC-ID Lisbon)",
